DURBAN - KwaZulu-Natal Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs (Cogta) MEC Sipho Hlomuka has expressed shock and sadness after the murder of eThekwini councillor, Minenhle Mkhize. Mkhize was gunned down on Saturday evening while he was entering his home in Cliffdale, west of Durban. Hlomuka said that the assassination of Mkhize has sent shock waves across the sphere of local government within the province.  “The forces that are hell-bent on destabilising this sphere will not succeed. We call upon law enforcement agencies to leave no stone unturned in their quest to apprehend the perpetrators of this ultimate act of cowardice.” Hlomuka added that members of the public who had  information about the murder needed to come forward and work with law enforcement.  “Similarly, we call upon our communities to come forward with information that will assist law enforcement agencies in their quest for justice. This murder has robbed the people of ward 103 of a young energetic leader who was committed to serving his community with humility and diligence.” Hlomuka conveyed his condolences to Mkhize’s grieving family.  “We wish to express our condolences to councillor Mkhize’s family, the community of ward 103 and his party the ANC.” EThekwini speaker Thabani Nyawose and members of the city’s executive committee visited the Mkhize family on Sunday to pay their respects. Nyawose said that the untimely death of Mkhize was a great loss to the municipality and the community of Cliffdale.  “Being a councillor is now becoming a dangerous job as they are constantly under siege. The municipality has lost one of its dedicated, young and hard-working councillors. His passing is a blow to the community of ward 103.” THE MERCURY